[{"type": "title", "data": "ED Major Burns"}, {"type": "category", "data": "Admit/Transfer/Discharge"}, {"type": "sentence", "data": "None"}, {"type": "note", "data": "Criteria for Referral to Burns Centre:\nConsultation and/or transfer to a burn center should be considered for all acutely burned patietns who meet any of the following criteria:\n1) Partial thickness burns greater than or equal to 10% of total body surface area (TBSA) in patients aged 17-50 years old, and partial thickness burns greater than or equal to 5% of total body surface area (TBSA) in patients aged 51 years and older \n2) Full-thickness burns in patients of any age\n3) Patients with partial or full-thickness burns of the hands, feet, face, eyes, ears, perineum, and/or major joints\n4) Patients with high-voltage electrical injuries, including lightning injuries\n5) Patients with significant burns from caustic chemicals\n6) Patients with burns complicated by multiple trauma in which the burn injury poses the greatest risk of morbidity or mortality. In such cases, if the trauma poses the greater immediate risk, the patient may be treated initially in a trauma center until stable before being transferred to a burn center. Physician judgment will be necessary in such situations and should be in concert with the regional medical control plan and triage protocols\n7) Patients with burns who suffer inhalation injury\n8) Patients with significant ongoing medical disorders that could complicate management, prolong recovery, or affect mortality\n9) Hospitals without qualified personnel or equipment for the care of patients with burns should transfer patients with burns to a burn center with these capabilities\n10) Burn injury in patients who will require special social/emotional and/or long-term rehabilitative support, including cases involving suspected abuse, substance abuse, etc\n", "value": ""}, {"type": "sentence", "data": "None"}, {"type": "note", "data": "See link for Adult Major Burn TBSA Burn E